Doc Spatz,<br><br>
I read the story. It is a work of fiction. The story line is real.<br><br>
I do not think too many people will be willing to open up on this topic other than to say that it did happen from time to time and to discuss the variety of reasons for its occurrence.<br><br>
In my own experience, feelings for the incompetance of the Officer Corps were exacerbated by frequent DEROS of experienced soldiers, the lack of unit cohesiveness, and the isolation of the individual in a fluid situation where personal survival was the cause at hand, not some political agends for medal thirsty neanderthal desk hogs from the Pentagon.<br><br>
I recall a sergeant major in Cu Chi who had to live in the<br>
equivalent of a bunker 24 hours a day because his manner was<br>
equated to worse than Vlad the Impailer, and the troops were<br>
frequently trying to blow him away.<br><br>
Grunt lore was full of fragging stories. We saw little if any of it in the artillery although my personal feelings included a few &quot;favorite&quot; outstandingly defective people whom I, myself, would have rather seen blown away. I chose, however, not to do it. Believe me, when you are armed to the teeth, and have motive and opportunity, both easy to come by in Nam, you did have a choice. 
